**Analysis of the Main Target Image**

From the supplied picture there are effectively _two_ separate little builds:

1) **Left “table‐like” structure**  
   - **Total of 9 blocks**  
   - At the center/top is one small **green** cube.  
   - Immediately around that green cube are four **blue** blocks forming a cross‐shaped top.  
   - Sloping outward at the base are four **orange** wedges (one on each “side” of the cross).

2) **Right “arched‐roof” structure**  
   - **Total of 2 blocks**  
   - A **red arch** block on the ground.  
   - A single **orange** wedge set on top front‐to‐back (creating a sloping “roof”).  

So in total, the target scene uses 11 blocks.

---

**Selecting Blocks from the Dictionary**

Below is the matching from the dictionary (no re‐orientations allowed other than exactly as pictured):

• **Green center**:  
  – 1 × Block #4 (the small green cube)

• **Four blue cross‐arms**:  
  – 4 × Block #8 (the small blue cube oriented with a face up)

• **Four orange wedges** (around the base of the “table‐like” shape):  
  – 1 × Block #13  
  – 1 × Block #14  
  – 1 × Block #15  
  – 1 × Block #16  
  (These four wedges each have a distinct “lean” so that all sides can slope outward without rotating them.)

• **Red arch (right‐hand build)**:  
  – 1 × Block #1 (red arch facing front)

• **Orange roof wedge** on top of the arch:  
  – 1 × Block #10 (wedge sloping front‐to‐back)

In summary, the needed indices (with quantities) are:
• #4 ×1  
• #8 ×4  
• #13, #14, #15, #16 (one each)  
• #1 ×1  
• #10 ×1  

---

**Assembly Order**

A simple way to place them (you may group by structure if you wish) is:

{
  Step1: Move block with index 4  
  Step2: Move block with index 8  
  Step3: Move block with index 8  
  Step4: Move block with index 8  
  Step5: Move block with index 8  
  Step6: Move block with index 13  
  Step7: Move block with index 14  
  Step8: Move block with index 15  
  Step9: Move block with index 16  
  Step10: Move block with index 1  
  Step11: Move block with index 10  
}

This completes the two structures exactly as shown in the target image without any extra rotations.
